      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 and FDA in-house FEA code both hold current ISO 9001 quality certifications; version-controlled solver executables with documented release notes.",
      "rationale": "All three FEA platforms (FDA research code, Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2, DePuy Synthes internal solver) are under version control with documented build and release procedures. ISO 9001 certification records reviewed and confirmed current. Gradation 2 is sufficient for a medium-risk Class II device validation at this model influence level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Each solver reproduces published benchmark problems (NAFEMS LE1, LE10) within 1% of reference solution.",
      "rationale": "Standard NAFEMS linear-elastic benchmark suite executed on all three solvers prior to study. Maximum deviation from reference solution was 0.7% (Ansys) and 0.9% (FDA code). DePuy Synthes solver passed equivalent internal benchmarks. Code verification is satisfactory at Gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates <2% change in all three QoIs between the medium and fine mesh; GCI < 5%.",
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study performed (coarse ~180k, medium ~620k, fine ~1.9M elements). Richardson extrapolation applied; GCI for stiffness 1.8%, yield force 2.3%, force at 40 mm 2.1%. All below 5% threshold. Achieved level 3 exceeds required level 2, providing additional confidence margin."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error characterization (iterative solver residuals, contact algorithm convergence tolerances, and nonlinear iteration path sensitivity) was identified as beyond the scope of the current submission. The assessment team noted that default solver tolerances were used and that a dedicated solver-error study was not conducted within the project timeline. This factor is therefore not-assessed. Given the model risk level of 3, this absence is acknowledged but not further justified in the current package."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "rationale": "Formal use-error assessment — covering analyst-to-analyst variability in boundary condition application, material assignment, and contact definition — was considered beyond scope for this initial submission. No inter-analyst reproducibility study was performed. The team deferred this factor to a future revision of the credibility evidence package, citing resource constraints and the availability of a single primary analyst for the model builds."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model form assumptions (linear elasticity for titanium alloy implant, rigid polyethylene block representation, frictionless contact at screw-block interface) are explicitly documented and supported by literature precedent and sensitivity analysis.",
      "rationale": "Linear-elastic constitutive model for Ti-6Al-4V is well-supported for sub-yield loading regimes. Sensitivity analysis confirmed that varying the polyethylene block modulus ±20% changed construct stiffness by <3%. Contact friction coefficient sensitivity (0.0–0.3) produced <4% variation in yield force. Model form assumptions are appropriate and documented at Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from ASTM-certified coupon tests on the same material lot; geometric inputs derived from CMM measurements of production implants with traceability documented.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V elastic modulus and yield strength obtained from tensile coupon tests (n=6) on the same material lot used for bench specimens; mean E = 113.4 GPa, σ_y = 924 MPa. Implant geometry digitized via CMM at ±5 µm tolerance. UHMWPE block properties from supplier datasheet with lot certification. All inputs traceable and within expected literature ranges."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 test specimens from production lot with dimensional inspection confirming conformance to drawing tolerances; specimens distributed across two independent laboratories.",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs tested; 6 at Laboratory A (FDA CDRH), 5 at Laboratory B (DePuy Synthes). All specimens from the same production lot, dimensionally inspected. Inter-laboratory coefficient of variation for stiffness was 3.1%, confirming specimen consistency. Sample size and distribution satisfy Gradation 2 requirements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions replicated per ASTM F1717-2021 with environmental controls documented; at least two test configurations (e.g., load levels or fixation angles) to bound the model response space.",
      "rationale": "Testing conducted strictly per ASTM F1717 at a single compression-bending load configuration (5° offset, 10 mm anterior translation). Only one test condition was employed, which is the standard F1717 protocol but does not provide multi-condition coverage to bound model behavior. Achieved level 1 falls below required level 2; this known gap is documented in the COU description and accepted by the decision team as a residual limitation of the standardized test method."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA boundary conditions and material inputs demonstrably match the physical test setup; any discrepancies quantified and shown to produce <5% QoI impact.",
      "rationale": "Boundary conditions in FEA replicate ASTM F1717 fixture geometry; rigid body constraints applied at grip locations confirmed equivalent to physical fixture stiffness (grip compliance <0.3% of construct compliance). Material properties mapped directly from coupon test data. Equivalency confirmed at Gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison using E/uval metric; acceptance threshold E/uval < 1.96 for all three QoIs; percent difference < 10% for each specimen-level prediction.",
      "rationale": "E/uval computed for all three QoIs: stiffness 0.94, yield force 1.31, force at 40 mm 1.74 — all below 1.96 threshold. Per-specimen percent differences ranged 0.8%–9.1%, all within the 10% bound. Validation uncertainty (uval) computed from experimental repeatability and measurement uncertainty per ASME V&V 40 Section 5. Output comparison satisfies Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are directly linked to the regulatory submission acceptance criteria and clinical failure modes documented in the risk analysis.",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs map directly to the predicate device comparison requirements in the 510(k) submission framework and to the primary mechanical failure modes (fatigue crack initiation at yield, gross deformation at 40 mm) identified in the device risk analysis. QoI relevance is fully documented and satisfies Gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities (ASTM F1717 bench testing of production implants) are representative of the COU (FEA-based design verification of the same implant family under the same loading regime).",
      "rationale": "Validation specimens are production-representative non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screws from the same design family as the COU device. The ASTM F1717 test protocol directly replicates the loading scenario modeled in FEA. The COU is design verification support for a 510(k) submission, and the validation activity was designed specifically to address this COU. Relevance is high and satisfies Gradation 2."
    }
